President meets senior Governing Board Members of the South Asian Federation of Accountants (SAFA)
President Abdulla Yameen Abdul Gayoom has met with senior Governing Board Members of the South Asian Federation of Accountants (SAFA), Mr. C. A. Suboodh Kumar Agarwal and Mr. Arjuna Herath, President and Vice President of SAFA, respectively. The SAFA delegation was joined at the meeting by Auditor General Mr. Niyaz Ibrahim.
At the meeting held this morning at the President’s Office, the Governing Board Members underscored the commitment of SAFA to developing and maintaining the quality of the accountancy profession in the SAARC region, and assured the President of their willingness to work closely with the Auditor General’s Office and other concerned Government authorities.

President Yameen expressed his gratitude to SAFA for their continued assistance to the accountancy  profession in the Maldives, and assured SAFA of the Government’s commitment to working alongside local and international partners to foster the development of local accountants. In this way, the President stated that the Government would welcome the establishment of an accountancy institute in the Maldives, in order ensure compliance of Maldivian accountants to international standards.
The meeting was attended by the Ministers at the President’s Office, Hon. Mohamed Hussain Shareef and Hon. Abdulla Ameen.

China trip successful in furthering opportunities- VP

Vice President Dr. Mohamed Jameel Ahmed has said that his recent trip to China has been very successful in furthering opportunities.
He made this remark speaking to the press after arriving in Ibrahim Nasir International Airport concluding his official visit to China, to attend the Opening Ceremony  of the 2nd China-South Asia Expo, and the 9th China- South Asia Business Forum.

Vice President stated that the official trip had been successful in furthering opportunities available to the investment, tourism, and renewable energy sectors in the Maldives.
The Vice President further noted that his official trip to China had re-affirmed international interest in investing in the Maldives, and had illuminated future trade opportunities between the Maldives and China.
Commenting on his meeting with the Governor of the Yunnan Province, Li Jiheng, Vice President Jameel stated that the Governor had assured him of the commitment of the People’s Government of Yunnan Province, to work with the Maldives in strengthening areas of cooperation.

Maldives begins its engagement at the 26th Session of the UN Human Rights Council
Maldives is participating in the 26th Session of the United Nations Human Rights Council which commenced today in Geneva.
The Maldives will engage in the debate on important human rights country situations such as the Syrian Arab Republic, Palestine and DPRK. The Maldives today responded to the opening statement by the High Commissioner for Human Rights, Ms. Navi Pillay, who made her final statement to the Council. The Maldives condemned the gross human rights violation of the rights of Palestinian people and expansion of illegal settlements by Israel, the occupying power. The Maldives expressed grave concern at widespread and systematic violence in the Syrian Arab Republic and the lack of response and action from the international community.

Praise be to Allaah.
There is a special day in Islam which Allaah has singled out for blessings which are not to be found in any other days. This day is Friday, to which Allaah guided the Muslims . It is the weekly festival of the Muslims, and it has many special features, some of which we will describe here:

1 – It was the teaching of the Prophet (peace and blessings of Allaah be upon him) to venerate this day, honour it and single it out for special acts of worship that belong exclusively to this day. In Fajr (early morning prayer) on Friday he used to recite the Soorahs (chapters) ‘Alif-laam-meem tanzeel’ (al-Sajdah, no. 32) and ‘Hal ata ‘ala’l-insaan’ (al-Insaan, no. 76).
Shaykh al-Islam Ibn Taymiyah (may Allaah have mercy on him) said: the Prophet (peace and blessings of  Allaah be upon him) used to recite these two soorahs in the Fajr prayer on Friday because they refer to what happened and will happen on that day, for they speak of the creation of Adam, the resurrection and the gathering of mankind, all of which happened or will happen on a Friday. So reciting them on this day is a reminder to his ummah (nation) of what has happened and what is yet  to come. This is one of the special features of Friday.

2 – It is mustahabb (recommended) to send lots of blessings upon the Prophet (peace and blessings of Allaah be upon him) on the day of Friday and the night before, because he said: “Send lots of blessings upon me on Friday and the night before.” (Narrated by al- Bayhaqi, 3/249; classed as saheeh (sound) by al- Arna’oot).
3 – Jumu’ah (Friday) prayers are held on this day; this is one of the most strongly-affirmed duties of Islam, and one of the greatest gatherings of the Muslims. It is the greatest and most obligatory gathering in which they come together, apart from ‘Arafah [a place near Makkah where the pilgrims stand and pray during the Hajj or pilgrimage]. Whoever neglects Jumu’ah prayers out of carelessness, Allaah will place a seal over his heart.
The people of Paradise will be brought closer (to Allaah) on the Day of Resurrection and they will see Allaah sooner, commensurate with how close they were to the imam on the day of Jumu’ah and how early they came  to Jumu’ah prayers.

Vice President visits Indira Gandhi Memorial Hospital, to observe renovation progress .

Vice President Dr. Mohamed Jameel Ahmed has yesterday morning visited Indira Gandhi Memorial Hospital (I.G.M.H) to observe its renovation progress.
During his visit, the Vice President surveyed the extensive work being undertaken to re-develop the hospital, and was briefed on the construction project currently underway to build an additional wing of the National Diagnostics Centre.
The Vice President also discussed with senior officials from I.G.M.H, efforts that could be undertaken to further improve the public hospital.

The ad hoc committee to review Standing Orders met yesterday for its second meeting.
Members considered suggestions sent to the committee by representing parties, and discussed the recommended omissions and additions. Maldives and Sri Lanka hold official talks
The Government of Maldives and Sri Lanka have held official talks yesterday.
The talks between the two governments were held at the President’s Office.
The official talks were led by President Abdulla Yameen Abdul Gayoom and the Sri Lankan President Mahinda Rajapaksa.
The President reiterated the government’s commitment to enhance the welfare of the people, develop and diversify the economy, strengthen social cohesion within the country, and empower the youth.
At the meeting, discussions were also held on the regional and international issues of mutual concern.

Cabinet finalizes guidelines through which uninhabited islands will be leased
The Cabinet has yesterday finalized the guidelines through which uninhabited islands will be leased for fisheries and agricultural purposes.
Referring to a paper prepared by the Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture, Members of the Cabinet had previously discussed the drafting of these guidelines, in the Cabinet meeting held on 15 June 2014.
In this regard, the Members deliberated the changes required to be brought to the existing draft of the guidelines. The Cabinet further decided on the implementation of the revised guidelines in the leasing of uninhabited islands for fisheries and agricultural purposes.
President Abdulla Yameen Abdul Gayoom also briefed the Cabinet on the details of the state visit to be made  by President Mahinda Rajapaksa of Sri Lanka.

Can you Explain some of the signs of Lailatul Qadr (the night of Decree)?
Question:
Answer:
The signs which indicate Lailatul Qadr which have been mentioned by the Prophet (SallAllaahu Alayhi wa Sallam), I can recall at this moment the following;
1. The first of them or number one is that Lailatul Qadr   is a peaceful, tranquil quiet night. Within that night or the night of Lailatul Qadr you do not hear the barking of dogs, or the sound of the cockerel.

2. The second sign is that in Lailatul Qadr the people experience a pleasant breeze or a pleasant wind which they enjoy which they like.
3. Thirdly, in Lailatul Qadr there is rain. This is one of  the signs of Lailatul Qadr that during the night of Lailatul Qadr the rain falls.

4. Fourthly, is that when the sun rises on the following morning the disc of the sun is seen without strong rays or is without any rays. The disc is a clear disc when it rises in the morning.
The shaikh said many of these signs the people notice them or they see them and if we notice these signs, then we should have glad tidings in the hope that we have coincided with Lailatul Qadr.
Shaykh `Ubayd al-Jaabiree

Fasting 6 days of Shawwal after Ramadhan. Q:
Is it true you have to fast the days that you owe from ramadan before fasting these 6 days. Ive heard that u must make up the days you've missed in Ramadan because these are obligatory whereas the 6 days in shawwal are sunnah. Any idea?
A:
1. If one fasts any 6 days (even makeups) in Shawwal, one gets the reward of performing the sunna of fasting six days of Shawwal, as the fuqaha have stated..

2. If one does the voluntary fasts first, and the makeups after, this would have more reward, though, if circumstances permit.
3. It is not obligatory to perform one’s makeup fasts before performing voluntary fasts, though one should  not perform the latter in a way that unduly delays finishing one’s makeups. This depends on one’s circumstances and adeptness at fasting regularly.
